      <hedline>
        <hl1>Will Faith Be an Issue for Voters?</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Robert Ouriel letter says David Margolick (August 12 Op-Ed) underestimates mainstream American public opinion when he implies that voters may not be ready for a Jewish vice president (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''For American Jews, Hope and Uncertainty'' (Op-Ed, Aug. 12), about Al Gore's choice of Joseph I. Lieberman as his running mate:</p>
        <p>David Margolick underestimates mainstream American public opinion when he implies that we may still not be ready for a Jewish vice president.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''For American Jews, Hope and Uncertainty'' (Op-Ed, Aug. 12), about Al Gore's choice of Joseph I. Lieberman as his running mate:</p>
        <p>David Margolick underestimates mainstream American public opinion when he implies that we may still not be ready for a Jewish vice president.</p>
        <p>While this country is certainly not a utopia of religious tolerance, we have come a long way since 1960, when John F. Kennedy's religion was indeed an issue to many.</p>
        <p>Today the majority of Americans -- the moderate middle, where this election will be decided -- seem to have no problem with Jewish political leaders, as evidenced by the fact that a good number of senators and representatives have been Jewish.</p>
        <p>ROBERT OURIEL  New York, Aug. 12, 2000</p>
      </block>
